{"/service/ndnp/vnstcsc/batch_vnstcsc_christiansted_ver02/data/sn84037526/00414181120/1921010801/0023.xml":{"full_text":"Londou, Jany. 4th.- Proposals for the\nformation of a corporation capitalized at\n\u00a3{O,O\\}C,OOO for the puarpose of raciliating\ntrade between Russia and Great Britain,\nwnich it is undersiood, had been ap\nproved g the Government and M. Kras\nsin, is Mnounced by the \u201c\"Times\u2019\u2019. The\nplans aw~ait tne action of the Russian\nbranch of the London Chamber of Com\nmerce on Jany. 12th. The corporation,\nhe capital of which will be subseribed\nequally by Russia and \u00a9reat BLritain, the\n\u201c{'imes\u2019\u2019 says, will be controiled \u2018by a\nBoard of Governor\u2019s selected hy both\ncountries.\nwasiington, Jany 4th \u2014A:surances\nthat the United States is not contempla\nting ioilitary intervention in Cuba ware\n\u201c*yiven today to the (\u2018uban Minister by\nSecretary .Jjaniels, 1+ was learned at the\nSrate Deparument\nDublin, January sth.\u2014Two rumours\nspread throuzh Dublin rapidly last night,\none that a manifesto \u00a3o the Irish peo\nle would be issued by Professog De\nvalera, ;the other that De Valera had\ncome to Dublin. Confirmatien of either\ncould not -he obtained in quarters usu\nolly well-informed on Sinn Fein affairs.\nIt is considered not unlikely. however,\nthat some message will be forthcoming\nfrom De Vaizra ina day or two. The\npublic may never know hoxy De Valera\nmanaged to reach Ireiand, and it is be\nlieved that the means by which he land\n~d in Ireland will be kept a s=cret, as\ncther Sinn Fein l-aders, absent from the\ncountry, may find it n\u00e9cessary Lo ufilize\nihe same ;plan. De Valera\u2019s presence\nin Ireland bhas been cenerally taken as\nmeaning a marked acceleration of the\nefforts to find 4 basis of :eace accepia\nbie to both sides. Since his arrival the\nDail Direann has n t held a meeting,\nbut one may be.arranged soon It is r:-\nsorted, in what is considered reliable\ncircles, that orders have been received\nfrom London forbdding the Crowp fore\nes to arrest D 2 Valera. The tension\nprevailing in Dublin before Christmas\npas greatly relaxed.\n$40,000,000 IN INCOME TAXES UN\nPAID IN NEW YORK\nTHOUSANDS MAY FACE GOVERNMENT\nPENALTY.\nQILK, TEXTILE, GARMENT, GROCERY AND\nAUTOMOBILE LINES HARDEST HIT AS\nRESULT OF DEPRESSION\u2014COLLCTOR\nEpwARrDS HoLps OuT HOPE OF\nReLIEF.\nWith the expiration at midnight last\nnight of the fime for paving the last\nquarterly instalment of Federal income\naxes it was estimated by William H.\nEdwards, Collector of Internal Revenue\nfor this distriet, that fuily $40,000,000 of\nthe $100,000,000 said to be due at this\n=1 gl 8 4N IE\ntime from residents of New York city\nwas still ungpaid\nHe was unable to give figuraes to show\nthe approxiimate number of delinquents,\nbut it is believed they run into the\ntnousands. All of them face a penalty\nof b per cent interest for failure to pay\non time and interest at the rate of 1\nper cent a m nth will be added.\nInability to pay the tax scemed to be\nwidespread. It affegyed the men of\nsmall means and many persons who a\nfew months ago could have paid tar\noreater amounts without feeling it., But\nthe general business depression, which\nhas swept over the country with in\ncreasing forece during the latter half of\nthe year, has wrought havoe without\nregard to persons and has played no\n{avorites.\nCollector Kdwards said that more peo-\nple had found it difficult to pay their\ntaxes than ever before. With some it\nwas impossible. They frankly told the\ncoliector so and said they would have\nro stand for the ilmposition of penalties.\nThose who thus took the collector into\ntheir confidence included brokers, busi\nness men, corner groceries and manutac\nturers.\nRegret Not Paving Pefore 4\nMany expressed regret that they had\nnot paid in full at the time the first\nquarterly instalment became dug last\nMareli. Monev was plentiful then and\nthey c\u00a2ould have done so, they said, but\nheld off in the hope of getting a little\nmore interest from their money hefore\nturning it over to the Government.\nNow, unable to get credit because of\nthe fall in value of their assets and\nwith money owed them co contr (s\nwithheld, or with contracts cance. d,\nthey could not pay.\n{Coliector kdwards declared that the\nsilk, Lextile, garment. grocery and auin\nmobile lines had been he pardest nit.\nIn the crowds which thronged the\ncorvidors of the Custom House yester\nday were many who were obliged to\npresent Liberiy bonds in settlement\nof claims. Thnis is the first time they\nhave been received here, but Collector\ntidwards announced they would be ac\ncepted only at market value.\nI'ne largest check reported yet was\nthat of one corporation for $3,164,000.\nThis incinded the quarterly instalment\nof income and excess profits tax. \u201che\nsmallest that came to notice was a quar\nterly payment on $10.38 made by a bare\nneaded Italian woman fron; the HKast\nSide, who rushed about the corridors in\nsearch of the cashier\u2019s window, eaver\nfearful that if she didn\u2019t pay Uncle\nSam would \u2018\u2018get her.\u201d\u2019\nEpwarps HoLbps Outr Hoprg.\nIn discussing the situation Mr. Ed\nwards said that as he had received no\ncommunication on the matter from Wash-\nington he dcubted reports that extensions\nwere being gr.... ed in other cities. He\ndeclarea that the evidence of the stlaigkt\nened condition, aburdart as it Fss Leen\nin his office, represents kvt 2 smail per\ncentage cf the actual runker i perscrs\nwho yesterday fcund tlenseives uretle\nto pay the tax.\nit was said that mavy individuals in\nraricus (ines of wnaushry kad lepciled\ntheir \u00abnalilidy to clicin lcars at e tonks\nand this jact mece the tighiness \u00a2f money\nall the m.cl\u00a2 eprarent cra aistressing.\nJourral of Commerce.\nLURE OF VESUVIUS.\nNEOPOLITANS CANNOT STAY AWAY FROM\nVOLCANO.\nJt is commonplace to say how reck\nless in men to build and live a!l about\nVesuvius and creep ever higher and\nhigher towaras its cone, huszbancing\nevery yard that will grow a vine nr\nvegetable, in spite ol the terrible les\nsons Vesuvius has taught them.\n\u201cdhe truth is.'\" says My .G A B\nDewar in his new book, \"\"A Younger\nSon,\u201d\u201d \u2018\u201c'the greater the lesson he gets,\nthe greater wiii be the recklessness of\nthe Neopolitan. If Vesuvius were a\nlive voleano in England instead of Ital\nthe same thing wonid be seen: a little\ntime after it had poured out lzva and\nmud and ash, and killed us in hundreds\nor thousands., and spoilt our homes and\ncrops, we should return tc Vesuvius\nand re-build.and creep up its sides anew.\nI suppose that sconer or later Vesuvius\nwill fly into a violent passion agzin, and\npour down her lava streams as she pour\ned them to Torre Arnuuziata not a gen\neration since.\n\u201c\"What a darkness Vesuvius might\nmake, you understand if you go down\ntu the shore by any of these towns, and\niook at the sand. It is black. The sand\nof the whole Bay of. Naples is black.\nWhen Vesuvius is in a passion, ashes\nfall in Rome, Genoa, Turin: they fall in\nParis.\nConceive all these towns spoiled to\nmorrow as Messina was spoiit by Etna,\nnone the less, in a ew years iime they\nwould, rise from the lava and mud and\nash finer than now. As Resina rose on\nHerculaneum, a uew Resina and a richer\n\"would rise on the old. The greater the\nbane of Vesuvius today, the greater the\nbalm to-morrcw. The ashes and mud\nturn to gold, you need not mueh kaow\nledge of the fruits of the earth to learn\nthat lesson.\nVesuvius will never [ose its hold on\nmen whiist ir remains active and terri\nble. it will only come into contempt\nand be lett to its:lf when its mud\nstreamns dry up and its ashes are all\nspent, for it is worth' nobody\u2019s while to\nlive tor long under an extinct volcano\u2122.\nBarbados Globe, Dec. 6th.","height":"18008","width":"14307"}}
